{"slug": "sorcerer", "root": "sorcerer", "category": "profession", "gloss": "a wielder of sorcery", "definition": "A sorcerer wields *sorcery* — magic figured as innate or fate-bending, worked by will and formula. Where a wizard studies, the sorcerer channels; the line is loose, but the sorcerer keeps a whiff of the illicit.", "history": "Buried in the word is an ancient practice: *sorcerer* comes through Old French *sorcier* from Vulgar Latin *sortiarius*, 'a caster of lots,' from Latin *sors, sortem*, 'lot, fate' — the same *sors* behind *sortilege*. A sorcerer was, at root, one who manipulates fortune by casting lots. The magical sense arrives in English around the 1520s. In Magic the word survives mostly as the card type *Sorcery*, a rules term now, far from its fortune-telling origin.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Etymonline, s.v. sorcerer", "where": "Etymology reference"}, {"label": "RenaissanceMagicDB, s.v. sortilegium", "where": "RenaissanceMagicDB"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Old French sorcier ← Vulgar Latin *sortiarius, from Latin sors, sortem (‘lot, fate’)", "first": "English c. 1520s (earlier ‘sorcery’ c. 1300)", "note": "A sorcerer is literally a ‘caster of lots’ — one who manipulates fate. The word hides an ancient divinatory practice inside it.", "hook": "Fate-casting: the dice buried in ‘sorcery.’", "lang": "Latin"}, "essay": {"title": "Sorcerer: the dice buried in the word", "dek": "Hidden inside 'sorcery' is an ancient technique — the casting of lots.", "read_min": 3, "html": "<p>A <strong>sorcerer</strong> and a <a href=\"term.html?t=wizard\">wizard</a> are, on the surface, the same thing — a worker of magic — but the words carry different weather. The wizard studies; the sorcerer <em>channels</em>, and keeps a whiff of the illicit the wizard has mostly shed. That difference is buried in the etymology, and it is a genuine surprise.</p><p><strong>Sorcerer</strong> comes through Old French <em>sorcier</em> from Vulgar Latin <em>sortiarius</em> — literally 'a caster of lots,' from Latin <em>sors, sortem</em>, 'lot, fate.' A sorcerer was, at the root, not a spell-slinger but a <em>diviner</em>: one who told fortunes and manipulated fate by casting lots, drawing straws, opening a book at random. The same <em>sors</em> gives us <em>sortilege</em>, which the RenaissanceMagicDB defines precisely as 'divination through the casting of lots — dice, marked objects, or randomly selected passages.' The magical sense we now hear arrives in English only around the 1520s, layered over that older fortune-telling core.</p><p>Magic: The Gathering has, without meaning to, buried the word even deeper. In the game <em>Sorcery</em> is a card <em>type</em> — a spell you can cast only at 'sorcery speed,' on your own turn — a purely mechanical term with no fortune-telling left in it at all. And yet the pun holds: every Sorcery is drawn from the top of a shuffled deck, a throw of the dice. The word came full circle to chance without anyone noticing.</p>", "sources": [{"label": "Etymonline, s.v. sorcerer (Latin sortiarius ‹ sors)", "where": "Etymology reference"}, {"label": "RenaissanceMagicDB, s.v. sortilegium", "where": "RenaissanceMagicDB"}, {"label": "the corpus (Sorcery card type)", "where": "Corpus"}]}, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 30, "oracle_total": 2292, "in_flavor_cards": 30, "in_oracle_cards": 2052, "name_match_count": 38, "by_variant": {"sorcery": 2284, "sorcerer": 22, "sorcerous": 6, "sorcerers": 4, "sorceries": 4, "sorceress": 2}, "first_year": 1994, "colors": {"B": 389, "G": 311, "U": 673, "R": 605, "W": 330, "C": 326}, "by_year": {"1994": 4, "1996": 10, "1997": 14, "1998": 7, "1999": 15, "2000": 12, "2001": 10, "2002": 3, "2003": 19, "2004": 22, "2005": 19, "2006": 10, "2007": 8, "2008": 11, "2009": 12, "2010": 21, "2011": 14, "2012": 30, "2013": 21, "2014": 25, "2015": 41, "2016": 36, "2017": 69, "2018": 38, "2019": 52, "2020": 105, "2021": 189, "2022": 254, "2023": 261, "2024": 341, "2025": 219, "2026": 216}}, "cards": [{"id": "3b102ccc-7629-457c-aba6-e9b00fd50c85", "name": "Emet-Selch, Unsundered // Hades, Sorcerer of Eld", "set": "FIN", "type_line": "Legendary Creature — Elder Wizard // Legendary Creature — Avatar", "rarity": "mythic", "colors": ["B", "U"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/7/5/75cf4eb8-33e7-4dfc-b890-a7e3b5c1b9d5.jpg?1782686432", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/7/5/75cf4eb8-33e7-4dfc-b890-a7e3b5c1b9d5.jpg?1782686432", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/fin/218/emet-selch-unsundered-hades-sorcerer-of-eld?utm_source=api", "local": "img/sorcerer/3b102ccc-7629-457c-aba6-e9b00fd50c85.jpg"}, {"id": "2ac2d483-2d2a-4912-8db4-04a5a2080831", "name": "Greensleeves, Maro-Sorcerer", "set": "DMC", "type_line": "Legendary Creature — Elemental Sorcerer", "rarity": "mythic", "colors": ["G"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/0/9/0969d7f3-cec5-4118-adb1-ff957eedf6ab.jpg?1782700685", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/0/9/0969d7f3-cec5-4118-adb1-ff957eedf6ab.jpg?1782700685", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/dmc/27/greensleeves-maro-sorcerer?utm_source=api", "local": "img/sorcerer/2ac2d483-2d2a-4912-8db4-04a5a2080831.jpg"}, {"id": "4da13eb8-ca18-43f1-b54b-d3ddceb980d2", "name": "Kadena, Slinking Sorcerer", "set": "C19", "type_line": "Legendary Creature — Snake Wizard Sorcerer", "rarity": "mythic", "colors": ["B", "G", "U"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/6/8/68a144f1-df18-4dc5-81c3-dff2af27527f.jpg?1782708123", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/6/8/68a144f1-df18-4dc5-81c3-dff2af27527f.jpg?1782708123", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/c19/45/kadena-slinking-sorcerer?utm_source=api", "local": "img/sorcerer/4da13eb8-ca18-43f1-b5